{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8916ded9-8327-45f3-a4cd-0da2a0c396b1","content":"To switch to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), you need to make these changes:\n\n**1. On nuget.org:**\n- Go to your package's settings → \"Trusted Publishers\"\n- Add a GitHub Actions publisher (owner, repo, branch/environment, workflow filename)\n\n**2. In your GitHub Actions workflow:**\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write  # Required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      # ... build/pack steps ...\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg \\\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n- **Add** `permissions: id-token: write` to the job\n- **Remove** `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` from `dotnet nuget push`\n- **Remove** the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret (once verified working)\n- Optionally use an **environment** in GitHub for additional protection\n\nThe `dotnet` CLI automatically detects the OIDC token from the GitHub Actions environment and authenticates with nuget.org without an explicit API key.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bcc63189-c083-4a78-bd8d-8c59867a2ad1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key (stored as a secret) to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet trusted publishing - I don't need to explore any codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about what needs to change.","outputTokens":413,"requestId":"1404:DC2FD:1CF21FD:2007FF5:69FA90C8"},"id":"104b711d-d6f4-4de5-b980-e95a8cd79e92","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:52:34.620Z","parentId":"8906729a-a132-4715-93ee-280794edc2ad"}
